{"type":"tool_call","subtype":"started","call_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Skw7yCkx3ppJjSe6iTvV7q","tool_call":{"editToolCall":{"args":{"path":"/home/AMD/khoffmey/dev/TraceLens/evals/unit_tests_comparative/test02_attention_both_unfused/analysis_output_ref/comparative_analysis.md","streamContent":"<!--\nCopyright (c) 2024 - 2025 Advanced Micro Devices, Inc. All rights reserved.\n\nSee LICENSE for license information.\n-->\n\n# LLM - Comparative Analysis: MI300X vs H100\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThis comparative analysis examines an unfused multi-head attention workload (BF16, 8 heads, seq_len=512, head_dim=64) across MI300X (Trace 1) and H100 (Trace 2). Trace 2 completes the same operations in significantly less GPU kernel time (0.12 ms vs 0.28 ms), indicating Trace 1 has optimization opportunities in both GEMM and softmax operations. The primary gap is in the batched matrix multiply (`aten::bmm`) where Trace 1 takes 2.25× longer, and softmax where Trace 1 takes 2.75× longer.\n\n| Metric | Trace 1 - (MI300X) | Trace 2 - (H100) | Difference |\n|--------|----------------------------|-------------------------------|------------|\n| Total Time | 0.28 ms | 0.13 ms | -0.15 ms (-53.6%) |\n| Compute % | 98.21% | 92.31% | -5.90% |\n| Idle % | 1.79% | 7.69% | +5.90% |\n| Exposed Communication % | 0.00% | 0.00% | 0.00% |\n| Top Bottleneck Category | GEMM (64.29%) | GEMM (66.67%) | — |\n\n{{PERF_PLOT}}\n\n---\n\n## Compute Kernel Optimizations\n\nFindings from per-category kernel analysis (GEMM, other).\nSummaries of recommendations from compute kernel sub-agents, focused on individual kernel efficiency.\n\n### Top Operations\n\n| Rank | Category | Trace 1 Time (ms) | Trace 2 Time (ms) | % of Compute Time | Ops | Difference (ms) | Potential improvement (time, E2E %) |\n|------|----------|-------------------|-------------------|-------------------|-----|-----------------|-------------------------------------|\n| 1 | GEMM | 0.18 | 0.08 | 64.29% | 2 | -0.10 | ~0.075–0.10 ms (26.79–35.72%) |\n| 2 | other | 0.11 | 0.04 | 39.29% | 1 | -0.07 | — |\n\n### 🔴 P1: Trace 1 attention BMM slower than Trace 2 pairing\n\n**Insight**: Trace 1 accumulates 0.18 ms of GPU kernel time on `aten::bmm` versus 0.08 ms on Trace 2 for the same 2 invocations and BF16 batch matmul shapes.\n\n**Action**: Pursue vendor GEMM paths and tuning that raise effective HBM bandwidth toward the 5.3 TB/s peak for these memory-bound shapes; consider whether fused attention or reduced intermediate traffic helps this memory-bound path.\n\n**Impact**: ~0.075–0.10 ms gap to target (26.79–35.72% of E2E)\n\n→ *See [Detailed Analysis: Compute kernel insights > P1](#detailed-analysis-compute-p1) for details*\n\n---\n\n### 🟡 P2: Close Trace 1 vs Trace 2 softmax kernel-time gap\n\n**Insight**: Trace 1 spends substantially more GPU kernel time on the matched `aten::softmax` than Trace 2, and this one op accounts for 39.29% of Trace 1 GPU time.\n\n**Action**: Diff the two runs (framework/library versions, attention fusion, inductor vs eager, and dispatch for `softmax_warp_forward`) and align Trace 1 with the faster Trace 2 configuration or kernel selection.\n\n**Impact**: Not quantifiable from trace data\n\n→ *See [Detailed Analysis: Compute kernel insights > P2](#detailed-analysis-compute-p2) for details*\n\n---\n\n## Kernel Fusion Opportunities (Experimental)\n\n> **Note:** Kernel fusion analysis is experimental.\n\nNo kernel fusion opportunities detected.\n\n---\n\n## System-Level Optimizations\n\n> **Note:** System-level analysis is exploratory. The patterns and recommendations below are under active development and may be refined as system-level analysis matures.\n\n> **Comparative note:** System-level analysis is performed on the primary trace (Trace 1) only. Cross-trace system-level comparison is not yet supported.\n\n✅ No system-level bottlenecks detected. GPU activity breakdown shows 98.21% computation, with negligible memcpy and communication overhead.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Analysis\n\n### Compute Kernel Insights\n\n<a id=\"detailed-analysis-compute-p1\"></a>\n#### 🔴 P1: Trace 1 attention BMM slower than Trace 2 pairing\n\n**Identification:** The row was flagged from aligned GPU kernel time: Trace 1 totals exceed Trace 2 for the same op name, shapes, and invocation counts on the comparative pairing. The op is memory-bound on Trace 1. (source: `gemm_metrics.json` → `operations[].time_ms`, `operations[].efficiency.bound_type`, `operations[].efficiency.resolved_peak_hbm_bw`, `gemm_ops.csv` → `lca_total_kernel_time_trace1_us`, `lca_total_kernel_time_trace2_us`, `delta_us (trace2 - trace1)`)\n\n**Data:**\n\n| Operation | Trace 1 Time (ms) | Trace 2 Time (ms) | Count (T1/T2) | Difference (ms) | FLOPS/Byte (T1) | Bound (T1) |\n|-----------|-------------------|-------------------|---------------|-----------------|-----------------|------------|\n| aten::bmm | 0.18 | 0.08 | 2 / 2 | -0.10 | 51.2 | memory-bound |\n\nOn Trace 1, achieved ~0.28 TB/s versus 5.3 TB/s peak HBM bandwidth (memory-bound peak reference).\n\n**Reasoning for Slowdown:** Trace 1 spends substantially more GPU kernel time than Trace 2 on the same batched BF16 matrix multiply work. Trace 2 finishes the paired invocations in roughly half the GPU kernel time Trace 1 requires, leaving a clear comparative gap to close on Trace 1.\n\n**Resolution:** Improving Trace 1 requires both reducing redundant memory traffic where the model allows and using better-tuned or better-selected vendor GEMM kernels for this memory-bound case. With ~51 FLOPs/byte on Trace 1, sustained time is dominated by moving operand and result bytes through HBM; kernels that move those bytes faster therefore finish each invocation sooner without changing the math.\n\n**Impact estimate:**\n\n- Low end (75% gap target): 0.075 ms savings (26.79% E2E)\n- High end (100% gap target): 0.10 ms savings (35.72% E2E)\n- Range: 0.075–0.10 ms (26.79–35.72% E2E)\n\n---\n\n<a id=\"detailed-analysis-compute-p2\"></a>\n#### 🟡 P2: Close Trace 1 vs Trace 2 softmax kernel-time gap\n\n**Identification:** The only row in this category is `aten::softmax` with high Trace 1 share of overall GPU time, while paired Trace 2 LCA kernel time is much smaller. (source: `category_data/other_metrics.json` → `operations[]`, `category_data/other_ops.csv` → `lca_total_kernel_time_trace1_us`, `lca_total_kernel_time_trace2_us`, `delta_us (trace2 - trace1)`)\n\n**Data:**\n\n| Operation | Args | Trace 1 Time (ms) | Trace 2 Time (ms) | Count (T1/T2) | Difference (ms) | FLOPS/Byte (T1) | Bound (T1) |\n|-----------|------|-------------------|-------------------|---------------|-----------------|-----------------|------------|\n| aten::softmax | (8,512,512) bf16 | 0.11 | 0.04 | 1 / 1 | -0.07 | — | — |\n\nKernel detail on Trace 1: `softmax_warp_forward<float, float, float, 4, true>`.\n\n**Reasoning for Slowdown:** Trace 1 takes about 2.75× longer than Trace 2 for the softmax kernel under the same LCA name, a 0.07 ms absolute gap on Trace 1. That is a straight pairwise comparison of GPU kernel duration, not a roofline shortfall.\n\n**Resolution:** Reconciling framework, compiler, and library paths between the two traces addresses the gap directly: a different `aten::softmax` implementation, fusion with surrounding attention math, or inductor-generated code on one side can change which warp-level softmax kernel is chosen and how much work remains fused.\n\n**Impact estimate:** Impact estimate is not quantifiable from trace data.\n\n### Kernel Fusion Insights\n\n> **Note:** Kernel fusion analysis is experimental. Savings estimates use a roofline projection model (75-100% of peak) with 85% memory/compute pipeline overlap. Kernels without perf models use their measured trace time as-is. Actual savings depend on implementation feasibility and interaction effects.\n\nNo fusion savings estimates available.\n\n### System-Level Insights\n\n✅ No system-level bottlenecks detected (idle time 1.79% is within acceptable bounds; no exposed memcpy or communication overhead identified).\n\n---\n\n## Appendix\n\n### Model Architecture\n- **Model**: LLM\n- **Architecture**: Transformer\n- **Scale**: Cannot be inferred from trace\n- **Precision**: BF16\n\n### Hardware Reference\n- **Platform (Trace 1)**: MI300X\n- **Peak HBM BW**: 5.3 TB/s\n- **Peak MAF (BF16)**: 708 TFLOPS\n- **Peak MAF (FP8)**: 1273 TFLOPS\n"}}},"model_call_id":"de66684d-d902-43fc-a184-f6f237127dea-56-oday","session_id":"254aeb55-f6f0-4bd2-bb42-0a4a9aed7e22","timestamp_ms":1777504814166}
